                <head>154. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On May 5, the Convention on Relations Between the Three Powers and the Federal
                    Republic of Germany entered into force, and the Allied High Commission ceased to
                    exist. In Berlin the Declaration on Berlin, signed on May 26, 1952, as amended
                    in the fall of 1954, also came into effect to govern the new relationship
                    between the three Western Powers and the city government. The texts of the
                    convention and declaration are printed in <ref target="frus1952-54v07p1#pg_112">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations,</hi>, 1952–1954, volume VII, Part 1,
                        pages 112</ref>–<ref target="frus1952-54v07p1#pg_128">128</ref>, and Part 2,
                    pages <ref target="frus1952-54v07p2#pg_1246">1246</ref>–<ref
                        target="frus1952-54v07p2#pg_1248">1248</ref>, respectively</p>
                <p>At the same time, the United States changed its representation to the Federal
                    Republic from a High Commissioner to an Ambassador, and in Berlin, from
                    Assistant High Commissioner to Chief of the Mission at Berlin.</p>
            </div>
